  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Marketing by Small-Farm Families from Indigenous and Rural Organizations of Imbabura and Pichincha</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">This project will be implemented in the provinces of Ecuador&#x2019;s northern Highlands, Imbabura and in Pichincha. Participating families working with two rural non-governmental organizations and with one second-tier organization (STO) have marketed their surplus produce in established rural fairs since 2006, but their production falls short of consumer demand. They have no permanent public locales for sale and local authorities do not effectively support these rural fairs. The first goal is for 210 original project participant organizations to increase their income over the next five years by selling surplus produce from their agroecological farms. The second is to build socio-organizational capacities in the STOs, including advocacy processes. The project seeks to increase farmers&#x2019; produce by increasing farm diversification; providing seeds and inputs; small and large animals; building animal corrals; planning production; and training in agroecology. Another objective is to reinforce marketing strategies, including setting up a regional marketing network; enhance family income; conduct organization-building for advocacy with local governments and other stakeholders. Another 210 families will benefit through Passing on the Gift.</narrative>
  </description>
